<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/6924174-rodzilla"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1522358577i/6924174._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/6924174-rodzilla">Rodzilla</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I&apos;m a little confused here. Brandon Sanderson is a strong writer who doesn&apos;t use swear words and doesn&apos;t have sex in his books. Yet I read the Mistbor<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I'm a little confused here. Brandon Sanderson is a strong writer who doesn't use swear words and doesn't have sex in his books. Yet I read the Mistborn series (which I enjoyed, BTW), and found blood dripping from the ceilings, vivisection, torture, and something along the lines of violent murder of the entire population of the world. They are probably the most violent books I have ever read. So I am unclear about what you mean by "clean," since you specified no graphic violence. Vivisection isn't graphic violence?<br /><br />And so i wonder about our standards as a culcture. Theoretically at least, sexuality is part of the normal human experience. Is vivisection? And is the mild sexuality or occasional swear word worse than what I read in the Mistborn series? Is there something I'm missing here?<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
