    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1054833593" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1054833593" />
    <a title="Eilonwy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17237503-eilonwy"><img alt="Eilonwy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1506803497p2/17237503.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1054833593?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eilonwy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eilonwy" href="/user/show/17237503-eilonwy">Eilonwy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780451450289" href="/book/show/1257796.Tigana">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Eilonwy by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/26681101-markus">Markus</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=character-driven">character-driven</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=deeply-thoughtful">deeply-thoughtful</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=heartbreaking">heartbreaking</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=heartwarming">heartwarming</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=beautifully-written">beautifully-written</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=good-worldbuilding">good-worldbuilding</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1054833593" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9012949089804036313"><br/><blockquote>The Peninsula of the Palm is a place divided -- but not against itself. Its nine provinces are occupied territory, under the power of foreign wizards. Brandin of Ygrath holds the east, while Alberico of Barbadior holds the west. Each state has been allowed to maintain its identity -- except for one, cursed to oblivion. <br/><br/>But a few people remember. They are determined to get their home back; and to free the entire Palm in the process.</blockquote>Before I can say anything else, I have to gush about the writing </span>
  <span id="freeText9012949089804036313" style="display:none"><br /><blockquote>The Peninsula of the Palm is a place divided -- but not against itself. Its nine provinces are occupied territory, under the power of foreign wizards. Brandin of Ygrath holds the east, while Alberico of Barbadior holds the west. Each state has been allowed to maintain its identity -- except for one, cursed to oblivion. <br /><br />But a few people remember. They are determined to get their home back; and to free the entire Palm in the process.</blockquote>Before I can say anything else, I have to gush about the writing in this book. Nearly every sentence is beautifully poetic and evocative in some way. That quality slowed my reading, but in a good way. I savored nearly every word on every page. If there’s an audio version of this book, I’d love to listen to it, because it seems meant to be read aloud. <br /><br />Nearly everything about this story was perfect. From the heartbreaking mood set in the Prologue through to the not-quite resolution of the Epilogue (argh, I’m going to be fretting about that off and on for a long time), the pacing, characterization, and introduction of information was all precise and just what was needed at that moment. The worldbuilding was very well done. The Palm, inspired by Renaissance Italy, felt like a real place. If I woke up there tomorrow, I’d know exactly where I was, and be glad to be there. <br /><br />The book did start off a little confusingly, with switches in POV from the prologue, then Chapter 1, and Chapter 2. But after Chapter 2 or 3 everything came clear (and I went back and read the first bits again, which helped reinforce some details I’d overlooked in my confusion). Four main characters -- youthful Devin and Catriana, and 30-somethings Alessan and Baerd -- form a band, literally (they’re all musicians, and music is woven into the story) and plot to overthrow the dictators. Parts of the story also follow Dianora, a member of Brandin’s <i>saishan</i> or harem, who carries a troubling secret. Some insights into Brandin and Alberico are provided, so they aren’t completely faceless monsters. <br /><br />The story is subtle, the build to a climax almost leisurely. Yet everything about it was compelling, and kept me flipping the pages and living in the book even when I wasn’t reading. And then just when I could barely stand wondering how the threads were all going to work out and come together, it all did, with some of the most gutsy, jaw-dropping, and heart-wrenching twists I’ve ever seen at the end of one volume. I felt completely wrung out when I closed this book -- in the best way possible. This is a story for which the details may fade in my memory, but the emotional impact will resonate for a long time. I’m already looking forward to rereading it in a couple of years. <br /><br />Highly recommended! </span>
  <a data-text-id="9012949089804036313" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


