    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1215038345" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1215038345" />
    <a title="Kaitlin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19126246-kaitlin"><img alt="Kaitlin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1481663259p2/19126246.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1215038345?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kaitlin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kaitlin" href="/user/show/19126246-kaitlin">Kaitlin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007342044" href="/book/show/7858391-tigana">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1215038345" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5338739050706314911">I&apos;m giving this book a 4* rating despite not being sure until the very last chapter about if it would be a 3*s or 3.5*s or 4*s. I was pretty sure by the time I finished up the book that it was a solid 3*s but I then read the author&apos;s afterword and he states all of his influences and what he wanted to achieve with the book and I decided that this had to be a 4* book because I totally understood where he was coming from and it really resonated true with me.<br/><br/>This book certainly feels a lot more hist</span>
  <span id="freeText5338739050706314911" style="display:none">I'm giving this book a 4* rating despite not being sure until the very last chapter about if it would be a 3*s or 3.5*s or 4*s. I was pretty sure by the time I finished up the book that it was a solid 3*s but I then read the author's afterword and he states all of his influences and what he wanted to achieve with the book and I decided that this had to be a 4* book because I totally understood where he was coming from and it really resonated true with me.<br /><br />This book certainly feels a lot more historical than many of the other fantasy books that I have read and there's a larger focus on the world building than many others too. I felt that this was a good thing as the focus was on renaissance Italy which is a period and place I really like, and therefore I was interested in learning how the author put his own spin on that time and integrated magic into that.<br /><br />The cast of characters are often my favourite aspect of the book and there certainly were a few who truly intrigued me, but I wouldn't say any of them truly captivated my adoration or that I was truly hooked into what happened to them. The main story has a cast of a few different characters and we collect more as we go, but the focus is largely on:<br />- Devin, a young singer who doesn't know a lot about the world or the political problems and intricacies of it but is an inquisitive boy nonetheless. He's a fun character and his impressions are frequently relayed to us about the goings-on that he becomes entangled in.<br />- Catriana, another member of the travelling band who's rather new and very mysterious to Devin and the others. No one really knows her backstory and she seems rather hostile towards others (with reasons we find out later on).<br />- Sandre is a very powerful Duke of Astibar and as the story begins his the fate of his (rich and powerful) family is unknown because he's seen 'drawing his last breath'.<br />- Alessan is a strange character with a sad, intense backstory. He's from a place few know of and he feels duty bound to a mission which is going to potentially change the fate of the land.<br />- Dianora is a young lady who has lived a life she never thought she would in order to achieve something she promised herself many years ago. However, there have been many complications to her plans not least a massive one which influences the course of the story a lot.<br />And many many more who we meet as the story goes on and the actions become larger and more influential.<br /><br />This story is set in a land ruled over by two Tyrants, the first is Brandin of Ygrath who is incredibly powerful and took over his land many generations before by suppressing and erasing the name and inhabitants of it. Due to Brandin the land of Tigana is no more and not only have its citizens been continually suppressed and worn down, but the name has been utterly erased from the language of men for all save those who were born there. Thus it means that the people who once knew Tigana as their home are forced to forget their old lives and subjected to the whims and wills of their new tyrant Brandin.<br /><br />The other ruler is Alberico of Barbadior who rules over Astibar and is the one who exiled Sandre (mentioned before) from his homeland and took over. He's probably the nastier of the two rulers over the course of this story and although they're both horrible for what they did and subjected the citizens of their dominions to, I felt that he was 'the bad guy' for me.<br /><br />Each of the tyrants obviously hates the other and not only do the hate one another but the people who have lost their homes or been forced to change their ways of life to fit the tyrants hate them, causing all sorts of warring, distrust and plotting behind the scenes which is really where the seedy side of things comes into play and it harks back to Renaissance Italy.<br /><br />The story itself was certainly an interesting one, although there were moments of 'weird' and 'slow' bits in the middle, it works really well as an overall standalone. I think the beginning and the end of the book were the strongest parts for me in terms of gripping me and being seriously interested. I felt like I couldn't put down the book at the end, I really enjoyed the ending and felt like the magic was pretty badass!<br /><br />Overall I just truly enjoyed this book for the majority and the whole premise of a land being completely suppressed and its inhabitants wanting to reclaim their homeland but being so unable to do so or unaware of the plans to do so was highly tension-filled. I loved the small band of people we gradually recruited to the scene and I enjoyed the fact that this book wasn't afraid to address things like incest and other 'taboo' subjects as it did so in a tasteful way,<br /><br />A solid 4*s and I will certainly look forward to my Guy Gavriel Kay in the future at some point, if you like strong plot and world building he seems to be your guy! (no pun intended :P)</span>
  <a data-text-id="5338739050706314911" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


